TI  - Research on Optimization of Multi-load AGV Picking System Operation Process
PY  - 2025
T2  - Proceedings of the 15th International Conference on Logistics and Systems Engineering
SP  - 1
EP  - 10
DO  - 10.52202/083767-0001
UR  - https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105031576411?origin=resultslist
AB  - The efficiency of single item picking operations is a crucial determinant of both the operational costs of warehouse systems and the competitiveness of logistics enterprises. In recent years, multi-load automated guided vehicles (MLAGVs) have been widely adopted in various picking systems due to their high load capacity and operational flexibility. However, compared to traditional automated picking systems, the MLAGV-based picking system presents significantly increased complexity and implementation difficulty. Consequently, improving the order picking efficiency of such warehouse systems has become a key focus and challenge in current academic research. This study aims to address the path finding problem of MLAGV picking systems and propose an effective solution to enhance their performance. To tackle the path finding problem of MLAGV picking systems, this study proposes a multi-agent proximal policy optimization algorithm integrated with curriculum learning (CL-MAPPO). The action space of MLAGVs is defined based on their driving characteristics and communication capabilities, ensuring that the actions taken by each AGV are realistic and feasible within the warehouse environment. A multi-dimensional reward function is designed, incorporating subgoal achievement rewards and path deviation penalties. This reward function guides the agent learning process by providing positive reinforcement for achieving intermediate goals and negative reinforcement for deviating from the optimal path. Additionally, the model is trained using a curriculum learning approach based on a path-splitting strategy. This strategy starts with relatively simple tasks and gradually increases the complexity of the tasks, allowing the model to learn incrementally and effectively enhancing the model’s training quality and convergence stability. Experimental results demonstrate that the proposed CL-MAPPO algorithm is highly effective in solving the MLAGV path finding problem within warehouse environments. Compared to other existing methods, CL-MAPPO exhibits excellent performance in terms of success rate, task completion time, and computational efficiency. Specifically, in scenarios with different scales of warehouse maps, numbers of tasks, and MLAGVs, CL-MAPPO consistently achieves higher success rates and shorter task completion times. Moreover, the computational time required by CL-MAPPO is significantly lower than that of other methods, indicating its superior computational efficiency. These results suggest that CL-MAPPO can effectively improve the order picking efficiency of MLAGV picking systems, thereby reducing operational costs and enhancing the competitiveness of logistics enterprises. This study successfully addresses the path finding problem of MLAGV picking systems by proposing the CL-MAPPO algorithm. The integration of multi-agent proximal policy optimization with curriculum learning enables the algorithm to learn incrementally and handle increasingly complex tasks effectively. The experimental results confirm that CL-MAPPO outperforms other existing methods in terms of success rate, task completion time, and computational efficiency, making it a promising solution for improving the order picking efficiency of MLAGV picking systems. Future research could explore further enhancements to CL-MAPPO, such as combining it with other advanced techniques like digital twin technology or machine learning models, to achieve even better performance in real-world applications. Additionally, investigating the scalability and robustness of CL-MAPPO under different operating conditions would be valuable for its practical deployment in various warehouse settings. Overall, this study contributes to the advancement of intelligent warehouse technologies and provides a solid foundation for future research in this field. © 2025 Proceedings of the 15th International Conference on Logistics and Systems Engineering. All rights reserved.
