AB  - Cyber-Physical-Systems (CPSs) are increasingly becoming integral to modern technological landscapes, characterized by their distributed nature and mixed-criticality requirements. Containers have emerged as a pivotal technology within CPS, offering process-level isolation with minimal runtime overhead, thereby facilitating the efficient distribution and execution of applications across multiple computation nodes. This distribution necessitates effective orchestration, leading to the complex Task Allocation Problem. In this paper, we introduce a novel approach to address Task Allocation Problems in mixed-critical CPS by formulating a Mixed-Integer Linear Programming (MILP) model. Our approach ensures that non-functional requirements, such as CPU, memory, and network constraints, are rigorously met. A distinctive feature of our model is its emphasis on worst-case failover times, which are crucial for mitigating hazards in critical applications. By focusing on these parameters, our solution not only optimizes resource allocation but also enhances the reliability and safety of CPS operations. This concept represents a significant advancement in the orchestration of distributed systems, providing a robust framework for managing the complexities inherent in mixed-critical environments. It has been evaluated with different task sets on reference hardware R-CAR H3, demonstrating its feasibility and efficiency to run mixed-critical containers in CPS. © 2025 IEEE.
