DO  - 10.1016/j.neucom.2025.130516
UR  - https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105005766813?origin=resultslist
AB  - The scale of robots in industry is growing up rapidly. Using data-driven methods to create tradable digital assets for large-scale devices is beneficial for achieving knowledge sharing and capability transfer among different users. The article implements an anomaly detection framework in robot manufacturing area, which are built by hybrid convolutional autoencoder. It approximates the dynamic model between motion and torque of robot, then, terminals judge anomaly with KL divergence between really torque and estimated torque. The framework shares those weight file as robot's digital asset to the distributed network and allow load balancing algorithm to apply to it. The article ultimately designed a scalable management system based on terminal clusters, which can adjust synchronously with the increase or decrease of device size to avoid overload and waste. The experiment shows that the proposed framework can ensure that each terminal's CPU usage is less than 62 % in the five-months durability and anomaly test. The RMSE for torque estimation is below 2 %, the F1-score for anomaly detection is over 99 %. Compared to previous time-series-based methods, there has been a significant improvement in the collected robot dataset. The proposed method has positive significance for establishing digital twin projects in real-time distributed information systems. © 2025 Elsevier B.V.
