UR  - https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105028200881?origin=resultslist
AB  - This article presents a novel approach for developing autonomous systems with self-assessment of state and functional awareness simulation for load-handling cranes, inspired by analysis of possibilities for adapting living organism traits in such systems. The novelty of the work encompasses application of comprehensive methodology integrating the developed parametric model of crane structure, simulation model, and discrete computational model with computational stability indicator of the system enabling analysis of its state and safety. The developed computational models enabled application of probabilistic neural networks for augmentation of simulation data with probabilistic self-assessment state classes representing the machine’s capabilities for self-care for its own state. The approach enables novel applications of embeddings and language models in autonomous systems for working machines and their mechanical systems. The developed methodology enables transformation of data from simulation models and empirical data from computational models into semantic spaces enabling the autonomous system to reason from patterns and anti-patterns of crane system configurations and working movements while ensuring safety of executed movements. Anti-patterns were developed that do not limit the space of possible load-handling system configuration solutions and safe working movement trajectories through modeling of self-assessment mechanisms for system stability state, operational structural loading, and positioning accuracy. Functional awareness simulation was realized through modeling the autonomous crane’s ability to imagine its own state after executing specific working movements and predict consequences of continuing movement sequences in critical configurations using the stability indicator for trajectory design in state space considering outrigger reactions, force distribution, and overturning moments. Building upon these foundations, a methodology for simulating state awareness and functional awareness from embedding spaces was developed through adaptive expansion to a large latent reasoning space representing synthetic working movements, enabling the autonomous system to generate awareness intensity curves modeling stability states and structural load states, culminating in final curves for simulation of both awareness types. The applied approach also encompasses the Physical AI concept through mapping of empirical mechanical dependencies onto semantic representations, opening new possibilities for development of autonomous mechanical systems with biomimetic self-assessment capabilities and functional awareness simulation. © 2013 IEEE.
