VL  - 320
C7  - 120317
DO  - 10.1016/j.oceaneng.2025.120317
UR  - https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/85214336186?origin=resultslist
AB  - As offshore energy expands into deep-water areas, floating production systems are crucial in offshore oil, gas, and wind power sectors. Umbilical cables, which connect floating platforms to subsea terminals, exhibit nonlinear dynamic responses due to their complex multi-material structure and underwater wave configurations. Accurate prediction of these stochastic responses is vital for high-computation scenarios such as design optimization, rapid prediction, and digital twin control. However, existing studies emphasize predictive accuracy neglecting model uncertainty. This study proposed a hybrid point-interval prediction method, BO-BiLSTM-ABKDE, for forecasting stochastic dynamic responses. The method combines data feature extraction, Bayesian optimization of bidirectional long short-term memory (BO-BiLSTM) neural networks, and adaptive bandwidth kernel density estimation (ABKDE). First, central moment feature extraction is used to enhance data expressiveness during preprocessing. Then, the BO algorithm searches for optimal BiLSTM hyperparameters to build a high-precision point prediction model. The BO-BiLSTM model, considering both data feature dimensions and different base models, demonstrates the best performance. Next, ABKDE is applied to estimate the probability density of prediction errors, generating prediction intervals various confidence levels to quantify uncertainty. ABKDE is superior to other interval forecasting methods in providing more reliable intervals. Finally, A case study on a lazy-wave umbilical cable validates the effectiveness of the proposed method, offering a viable solution for similar engineering challenges. © 2025 Elsevier Ltd
