TI  - Automated Moving Target Defence in OT Security: Dynamic IP-enabled VLAN and Port Shuffling
PY  - 2025
T2  - 2025 3rd International Conference on Artificial Intelligence and Automation Control, AIAC 2025
SP  - 98
EP  - 105
DO  - 10.1109/AIAC68175.2025.11332276
UR  - https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105032626208?origin=resultslist
AB  - Operational Technology (OT) environments have conventionally relied on legacy systems with static Internet Protocol (IP) addressing, often lacking security features. This poses challenges to integrating dynamism, which is essential for security and resilience. The proposed solution is an Automated Moving Target Defence (AMTD) leveraging OpenFlow and NetConf/YANG models in Software-Defined Networking (SDN). Referring to the Open Systems Interconnection (OSI) network model, this innovative approach introduces the shuffling of Layer 2 IEEE 802.1Q Virtual Local Area Networks (VLANs), Layer 3 IP-enabled VLAN Interfaces, and Layer 4 Transport Control Protocol (TCP) Ports to disrupt an attacker's ability to understand, map, and persist within the network. An experimental enhanced fidelity virtualised cyber-physical system (CPS) testbed has been developed to demonstrate the practicality of the AMTD shuffling method, closely aligning with real-world scenarios. The study evaluates the AMTD method's impact on system performance and underscores its potential contributions to enhancing OT cybersecurity while preserving critical processes. This research uses an industrial case study of a simulated virtual wastewater treatment plant communicating over the Open Platform Communications Unified Architecture (OPC-UA) protocol. © 2025 IEEE.
