TI  - AI-Based intelligent edge autonomous control technology for energy conservation and carbon reduction in smart public buildings
PY  - 2025
T2  - Proceedings of 2025 8th International Conference on Computer Information Science and Artificial Intelligence, CISAI 2025
SP  - 784
EP  - 790
DO  - 10.1145/3773365.3773489
UR  - https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105026341743?origin=resultslist
AB  - Under the "Dual Carbon"goals, public buildings represent a major sector for energy consumption and carbon emissions in the construction industry, making energy-efficient and low-carbon development of public buildings a critical priority for China's low-carbon urban development objectives. To address challenges such as the lack of real-time user behavior interaction, prolonged operation of HVAC and lighting systems in unoccupied spaces, and inappropriate temperature settings in public buildings. This study proposes an AI-based intelligent edge autonomous control system for smart public buildings. This system, designed around user behavior, integrates artificial intelligence, machine learning, the Internet of Things (IoT), big data, cloud computing, and digital twin technologies to establish a real-time, self-updating building model with automated control. It could ensure compatibility between public building environments and user scenarios while delivering an effective solution for energy conservation and carbon reduction. The system employs millimeter-wave radar sensors to autonomously detect and assess occupancy, temperature, humidity, illuminance, and air quality within public building spaces. Additionally, it utilizes AI-powered edge computing to perform 24/7 automated decision-making for offices, meeting rooms, and open areas based on zonal management objectives and user behavior patterns, issuing real-time control commands to terminal devices to achieve energy and emission reductions. A pilot implementation in an office building validated the system's feasibility, with energy performance data demonstrating that the intelligent edge autonomous control system enables zonal management, effectively resolving delays in environmental energy management and minimizing energy waste. The system reduces operational energy consumption and carbon emissions by over 25%, confirming its significant impact on public building sustainability. © 2025 Copyright held by the owner/author(s).
