TI  - A DRL-based Cyber-Physical Control Framework for Real-Time Maritime Collision Avoidance
PY  - 2025
T2  - Proceedings of 3rd International Conference on Intelligent Cyber Physical Systems and Internet of Things, ICoICI 2025
SP  - 693
EP  - 699
DO  - 10.1109/ICoICI65217.2025.11252815
UR  - https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105030331978?origin=resultslist
AB  - In order to meet the challenge of real-time collision avoidance control of intelligent ships under complex sea conditions, this study proposed a deep reinforcement learning policy optimization algorithm TE-TRPO (Transformer-Enhanced Trust Region Policy Optimization) that integrates the Transformer structure. The algorithm is based on the Markov decision process and introduces a multi-head attention mechanism to improve the modeling ability of the policy network for complex environmental states. At the same time, the model uses trust region policy optimization to ensure the stability of policy updates, and combines the Adaptive Swarm Evolution Search (ASES) mechanism to achieve adaptive adjustment of the policy network structure and hyperparameters. To ensure the physical interpretability of the control strategy, this study constructs a ship rolling dynamics model considering wind and wave interference and uses a differential recursive formula to achieve simplified modeling of the control system. At the same time, this study integrates multi-source data input (AIS, radar, GPS, sonar) in the perception layer and dynamically predicts the future trajectory of the target ship through TCN and LSTM. In the risk assessment mechanism, this study introduces event-driven joint collision probability modeling logic to enhance the control robustness of the system under sudden risks. The experimental part is based on a simulation environment with multiple targets, multiple obstacles, and multiple weather interferences. Three typical navigation scenarios are set up and compared with the traditional COLREG rule strategy and PPO algorithm. The results show that the TE-TRPO method proposed in this paper is superior to the comparison method in seven indicators, including collision avoidance success rate, path deviation, fuel efficiency, and control stability.  © 2025 IEEE.
