AB  - Small and medium-sized enterprises (SMEs) in precision manufacturing face significant barriers to Industry 4.0 adoption, including high costs, technical complexity, and vendor lock-in. This paper presents a locally deployable Industrial Internet of Things (IIoT) platform that addresses these challenges through three integrated solution components. First, we implement metadata standardized digital interfaces using containerized Asset Administration Shell (AAS) implementations. Second, our assisted asset modeling approach employs visual markers to semi-automatically generate digital twins and AAS models. Third, we provide an open-source low-code development environment, where technicians create automation workflows through visual programming of function blocks deployed as microservices. The platform integrates legacy equipment through an adaptive I/O layer supporting multiple industrial protocols (OPC-UA, Modbus, MQTT). Unlike vendor-specific solutions requiring extensive IT expertise, our standardized metadata integration method ensures complete data sovereignty through local deployment on lightweight container runtime. Technical validation in our manufacturing laboratory demonstrated: 97% reduction in calibration time (30 minutes to 1 minute), 40% personnel cost reduction enabling basic operators to replace specialist technicians, and elimination of software licensing dependencies. Deployment complexity was reduced by 70% through automated configuration, enabling manufacturing technicians to manage operations after initial IT-assisted setup, with communication time below 100ms from machine to client (all machine data). © This is an open access article published by the IET under the Creative Commons Attribution License (http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/3.0/)
