TI  - Wearable technology for blockchain-enabled smart healthcare applications using flexible piezoelectric materials and strain measurement devices
PY  - 2025
T2  - Mechanics of Advanced Materials and Structures
DO  - 10.1080/15376494.2025.2512181
UR  - https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105007536517?origin=resultslist
AB  - The increasing demand for ongoing and secure health monitoring has resulted in the amalgamation of wearable biosensors with advanced cyber-physical systems. Although piezoelectric materials provide a promising basis for self-powered physiological monitoring, their dependence on wireless networks presents considerable cybersecurity issues. This study introduces an innovative framework that integrates flexible piezoelectric sensors with blockchain technology and artificial intelligence (AI) to facilitate safe, real-time healthcare monitoring. We develop a dual-layer architecture that differentiates edge and core networks to enhance system scalability and robustness. Simulated cyberattacks, such as port scans, Distributed Denial of Service (DDoS) attacks, and Man-in-the-Middle (MitM) intrusions, are performed to detect system weaknesses and assess defensive measures. An efficient ResNetV2-based AI model is utilized to identify threats with great precision, while blockchain technology guarantees immutable data integrity. Experimental assessments utilizing synthetic healthcare data validate the framework’s accuracy, scalability, and robustness against network-based attacks. The suggested system rectifies deficiencies in real-time anomaly detection, secure data transfer, and energy-efficient wearable design. It establishes the foundation for the advancement of next-generation intelligent and cyber-resilient smart healthcare platforms. © 2025 Taylor & Francis Group, LLC.
