DO  - 10.1016/j.compeleceng.2026.111095
UR  - https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105032189507?origin=resultslist
AB  - This study presents a dynamic risk quantification model for the Maritime Internet of Things (MIoT) based on an integrated framework combining the STRIDE (Spoofing, Tampering, Repudiation, Information Disclosure, Denial of Service, Elevation of Privilege) threat model with the Analytic Hierarchy Process (AHP) and Fuzzy Comprehensive Evaluation (FCE) methods. The framework employs digital twin simulations to validate its effectiveness, achieving an impressive assessment accuracy of 92.3%, outperforming traditional approaches. Key innovations include the introduction of topological weight and dynamic attack exposure indicators, supported by scientifically determined weight allocation and uncertainty handling through AHP-FCE. This framework not only facilitates risk visualization and prioritization of protective measures, enhancing resource utilization by over 30%, but also establishes a direct correlation between theoretical constructs and practical applications in maritime security. While the model demonstrates robust performance in simulation settings, challenges such as parameter dependency and adaptability to novel threats persist. Future research may explore the integration of machine learning for adaptive parameter optimization and investigate the application of blockchain and zero-trust architectures to reinforce the security of maritime operations. © 2026 Elsevier Ltd.
