DO  - 10.1109/TEMSCONGlobal64363.2025.11238282
UR  - https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105031387103?origin=resultslist
AB  - Modern supply chains are increasingly vulnerable to global disruptions such as port congestion, supplier delays, and geopolitical instability. Traditional planning systems often struggle to simulate and evaluate the impact of such disturbances on operational performance. This paper presents a disruptive digital sandbox, a lightweight machine learning-powered simulation framework designed to analyze supply chain resilience strategies in synthetic environments. The sandbox is built on a simulated multi-tier supply chain dataset that incorporates time series logistics data, sourcing dependencies, and disruption variables. Predictive models, including XGBoost and bidirectional long-short-term memory (Bi-LSTM) networks, are trained to classify the outcomes of disruption. The framework supports scenario-based simulations, allowing users to toggle various types of disruption and observe their downstream effects in real time. A key feature of the framework is its modular model integration, allowing users to select and plug in different machine learning algorithms depending on their needs for accuracy, interpretability, or scalability. The results demonstrate the framework's ability to quantify resilience metrics and offer actionable insights into lead time volatility, service level degradation, and cost variation under stress conditions. This proposed sandbox offers a flexible and data-driven approach to disruption planning without requiring proprietary data or full-scale digital twin infrastructure.  © 2025 IEEE.
