AB  - In this paper, a finite-time control method aimed at mitigating the disturbance caused by a cutting-in human driving vehicle (HV) to a stable mixed traffic platoon is investigated, with a particular focus on addressing its convergence challenges in a two-lane scenario in the vicinity of traffic signals. Firstly, with the goal of passing the traffic signals without stopping in the mixed traffic platoon, the Connected Autonomous Vehicle (CAV) speed control strategy for the mixed vehicle platoon is designed by using the MPLF communication topology. On this basis, considering the urgency of forced lane change and the need to meet the needs of the platoon’s rapid recovery of stability, a finite-time coupling control strategy based on a non-singular fast terminal sliding mode controller is designed. The simulation results show that the proposed method has good performance against the cut-in disturbance, which can also reduce the exhaust CO2 emissions. © ASCE.
