AB  - The conventional Industry 4.0 architecture of manufacturing and warehousing is hardware-centric, limiting flexibility and adaptability. The material handling systems deploy heterogeneous multiple agents that have an application or environment-specific discrete control layer. This work presents the concept of a Software-Defined Factory and its control system for a software-centric control. The software-defined factory integrates industrial hardware and software systems, hosting the control system, AI, simulation, and digital twins to enable seamless material flow throughout the factory through heterogeneous multi-agent control. The presented control system has a centralized architecture designed with a bottom-up approach for commercial systems. It manages communication, localization, navigation, and task allocation in a heterogeneous multi-vendor fleet deployed in real-world scenarios. The latency, accuracy, repeatability, planning-level scalability, and path execution evaluations of the proposed system were conducted with heterogeneous fleets. The operation of overhead hoist transport vehicles with automated guided vehicles on a scaled semiconductor manufacturing shop floor demonstrated heterogeneous hardware integration for material handling in industrial settings. The proposed system has potential to mitigate major challenges in deployment, data interoperability, and hardware dependency for diverse industrial applications, including manufacturing, warehousing, and inspection. © 2026
