TI  - Real-time delay detection and risk analysis management in civil construction projects using AI-driven framework
PY  - 2026
T2  - International Journal of Construction Management
DO  - 10.1080/15623599.2026.2636733
UR  - https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105032130721?origin=resultslist
AB  - High-rise construction faces critical delays due to floor cycle overruns, vertical transport bottlenecks, and resource volatility. This study proposes an AI-driven framework for real-time delay detection and proactive risk analysis. The methodology integrates Adaptive Temporal-Spatial Noise Suppression (ATSNS) for high-fidelity data pre-processing and Dynamic Feature Relevance Adjustment (DFRA) to prioritize critical factors like crane utility and reinforcement congestion. Real-time monitoring is achieved through Spatio-Temporal Pattern Recognition (STPR), synchronizing IoT sensors and drone telemetry with engineering baselines. Experimental validation on complex high-rise projects yielded a testing accuracy of 97.8%, with precision and recall reaching 97.2% and 98.0%, respectively. These results significantly outperform conventional Decision Tree, Random Forest, and LSTM models. The framework enables early anomaly detection, improving schedule adherence and operational efficiency. While current limitations include high dependency on sensor coverage and computational power, the system provides a robust foundation for intelligent construction management. Future research will focus on integrating predictive digital twins for multi-site coordination and real-time scenario optimization, further advancing data-driven decision-making in the high-rise building sector.High-rise construction faces critical delays due to floor cycle overruns, vertical transport bottlenecks, and resource volatility. This study proposes an AI-driven framework for real-time delay detection and proactive risk analysis. The methodology integrates Adaptive Temporal-Spatial Noise Suppression (ATSNS) for high-fidelity data pre-processing and Dynamic Feature Relevance Adjustment (DFRA) to prioritize critical factors like crane utility and reinforcement congestion. Real-time monitoring is achieved through Spatio-Temporal Pattern Recognition (STPR), synchronizing IoT sensors and drone telemetry with engineering baselines. Experimental validation on complex high-rise projects yielded a testing accuracy of 97.8%, with precision and recall reaching 97.2% and 98.0%, respectively. These results significantly outperform conventional Decision Tree, Random Forest, and LSTM models. The framework enables early anomaly detection, improving schedule adherence and operational efficiency. While current limitations include high dependency on sensor coverage and computational power, the system provides a robust foundation for intelligent construction management. Future research will focus on integrating predictive digital twins for multi-site coordination and real-time scenario optimization, further advancing data-driven decision-making in the high-rise building sector. © 2026 Informa UK Limited, trading as Taylor & Francis Group.
