AB  - The rapid expansion of the Power Internet of Things (PIoT) has led to widespread deployment of terminal devices such as smart meters, sensors, and controllers in modern smart grids and renewable energy systems. These terminals play a critical role in enabling real-time monitoring, intelligent control, and data-driven decision-making. However, their distributed nature, limited computational capacity, and exposure to untrusted environments make them increasingly vulnerable to a wide range of cyber-physical threats. This paper presents a comprehensive review of existing security frameworks aimed at protecting PIoT terminals, with a focus on cryptographic authentication mechanisms, edge computing architectures, and AI-driven anomaly detection techniques. Explore the limitations of traditional Public Key Infrastructure (PKI) models, the emergence of lightweight Identity-Based Cryptography (IBC), and the integration of Secure Access Modules (ESAM) for terminal authentication. The role of edge computing in offloading security tasks and enhancing localized defense is examined, along with deep learning approaches for intrusion detection and botnet prevention. By analyzing over 100 recent studies, we provide a structured synthesis of threat categories, defense technologies, and practical implementations across smart grid environments. The paper concludes by outlining open research challenges and proposing future directions for developing scalable, intelligent, and energy-efficient security solutions tailored to the unique constraints of power IoT terminals. © 2026 Elsevier Ltd
