AB  - In the era of the Industrial Revolution 4.0, the integration of cyber-physical systems (CPS) has become a dominant paradigm across various industrial sectors. However, this extensive network connectivity introduces new challenges related to cybersecurity, where cyber-attacks have the potential to disrupt the stability and operational efficiency of industrial systems. Specifically, attacks causing time delays in industrial processes can significantly impact system performance, including the three-tank control system that is the focus of this research. To address these vulnerabilities, this study proposes the design of a resilience control system against cyber-attacks by utilizing the time-delay independent Lyapunov-Krasovskii functional approach. This method is chosen due to its proven capability in analyzing and ensuring system stability with unknown time delays, thereby enhancing system resilience against disturbances and cyber-attacks. This research aims to design and implement a control system capable of maintaining the stability and performance of the three-tank system under the threat of cyber-attacks that cause time delays. The Lyapunov-Krasovskii approach is used to develop time-delay dependent stability criteria, which are then integrated into the controller design. This method enables a more accurate and conservative analysis of system stability, providing better performance guarantees in the face of uncertainties and disturbances. © 2025 IEEE.
