AB  - The growing global food demand has intensified the need for sustainable fisheries. This challenge has become intractable as major maritime nations like Japan face a declining fishery workforce, and approximately 60% of coastal fish stocks are assessed at low levels. Sustainable fishery management is an urgent priority. While various remote sensing technologies have been applied to the ocean to support smart fisheries, their effectiveness remains limited. This paper proposes an ocean digital twin (ODT), enabled by connected off-grid smart buoy systems that integrate sonar sensors, low-earth orbit (LEO) satellite communication systems, and solar panels. This system allows the real-time collection of high-resolution sensing data across the entire ocean. We conduct proofs of concept in Suruga Bay by prototyping the smart buoy system and performing fish catch prediction with data from ODT and historical fishery reports. It turns out that the prediction accuracy is sufficient to promote efficient fisheries and contribute to resource management. Moreover, the LEO communication performances on buoys are revealed for the first time worldwide.  © 2025 Marine Technology Society.
