DO  - 10.1016/j.cie.2026.111882
UR  - https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105029470474?origin=resultslist
AB  - Industrial 5.0 is driving the manufacturing industry toward deeper human–machine collaboration. Distributed flexible job shop scheduling that incorporates worker factors has emerged as a key research area for improving production efficiency. Automated guided vehicles (AGVs) play an important role in automated production. However, the limited availability of AGVs often poses challenges in meeting diverse transportation demands within complex production environments. Workers, owing to their adaptability and learning capabilities, can offset equipment limitations and improve scheduling efficiency. This paper investigates a novel distributed flexible job-shop scheduling problem with worker-AGV collaboration (DFJSP-WAC). First, a digital worker model and a mixed-integer linear programming model are developed for DFJSP-WAC. Next, a hierarchical multi-agent architecture is employed to decompose the scheduling tasks, in which the high-level agent performs global optimization, and low-level multi-agents make specific decisions. Deep residual networks are integrated to address the vanishing gradient issue during model training. Finally, experiments are conducted in a digital twin environment using multiple randomly generated cases and extended public datasets for validation. The experimental results show that the proposed algorithm consistently outperforms existing methods, yielding more than a 35% reduction in average makespan compared with non-human-AGV collaborative scheduling approaches under constrained transportation resources. This highlights the effectiveness of the proposed framework in efficiently solving human-AGV collaborative scheduling problems. © 2026 Elsevier Ltd
