AB  - NetLogo is widely used for agent-based simulation of transport and logistics because it is open, flexible, and fast to prototype. This review synthesizes peer-reviewed studies on NetLogo across four application streams: (a) Intelligent Transport Systems (ITS) and flow optimisation; (b) Public-transport operations and evacuation management; (c) Traffic-control, energy use, emissions analysis; and (d) Driver/vehicle behaviors and connected/autonomous vehicle modelling. We map how agent rules, interaction topologies, and calibration choices shape material, information, and human flows across networks and terminals, and how they inform transport operations, distribution logistics, and supply chain decisions. A thematic synthesis highlights five recurring gaps: (1) Oversimplified agent size/geometry; (2) Limited behavioral realism for drivers, passengers, and controllers; (3) Weak mesoscopic linking between macro demand and micro operations; (4) Short time horizons for dynamics of congestion and energy; and (5) Incomplete calibrationverification-validation. We propose a logistics-oriented research agenda: multi-scale coupling (macro–meso–micro), behavior learning with ML, real-time digital-twin use cases, standardized CV&V protocols, and energy-emissions cometrics. The review clarifies where NetLogo adds value to transport logistics-rapid what-if testing of control policies, routing, and terminal operations-while outlining steps needed for rigorous, decision-grade models. © Acta Logistica, www.actalogistica.eu.
