UR  - https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105026285077?origin=resultslist
AB  - Access to high-quality maritime data is often restricted, creating significant barriers for academic institutions or non-maritime organizations to participate in technology development. To address this challenge and accelerate digital transformation in the maritime industry, we propose providing real-ship navigation data and a real-time testbed. This study focuses on developing a data collection system and testbed based on a digital twin concept as a platform for research and development. The system is designed to capture data nearly equivalent to the information obtained by a human on a ship's bridge. It includes visual data from around-view cameras and X-/S-band radar videos with motion responses measured by an Inertial Measurement Unit (IMU). These datasets are essential for developing navigation technologies to ensure safe and efficient operation of ships. The platform adopts a software containerization technology combined with the digital twin concept. It allows researchers to execute their programs in a secure environment with retrieving real-time data through the digital twin interface. Furthermore, as the platform onboard is connected to the internet via Starlink, programs running on it can be seamlessly integrated with cloud-based AI models. The platform is scheduled to be installed on a large commercial vessel in 2025. © 2025 by the International Society of Offshore and Polar Engineers (ISOPE).
