TI  - Development and Optimization of an Operations Concept for a Dual-LiDAR Component of the Earth Return Orbiter
PY  - 2025
T2  - Proceedings of the International Astronautical Congress, IAC
SP  - 348
EP  - 355
DO  - 10.52202/083086-0042
UR  - https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105032498878?origin=resultslist
AB  - The Mars Sample Return (MSR) program, led by NASA and ESA, aims to return Martian rock samples to Earth. The ESA’s Earth Return Orbiter (ERO) will capture a basketball-sized sample container in low Mars orbit, using a Dual-LiDAR system for close-range navigation and target tracking from 1 km down to 1 meter. This paper explores the use of scenario-based simulation to develop and optimize an Operations Concept for the Dual-LiDAR system that covers the initial target acquisition and target tracking during the approach phase. For this purpose, the authors created Digital Twins of the orbiter, the LiDARs and the target within the Virtual Testbed for Space Applications (VTSA). By means of detailed physics-based simulation, this enables the analysis of the main operational parameters of the LiDARs (e.g. field-of-view and angular resolution) and their impact on metrics such as tracking robustness and detection errors under different relative motion velocities. The biggest challenge when using a 3D LiDAR at long distances, is to balance the angular resolution and the field of view so that the LiDAR pulses reliably hit the target and it remains in the field of view, even if there are relative translational and rotational movements between the orbiter and the target. To investigate this in detail, a method was developed that uses formal scenario descriptions to generate a large number of scenario variants. These variants are then automatically executed and analyzed using Digital Twins in VTSA. This process determines the optimal LiDAR parameters for all possible scenario variants. Then, the optimized parameter sets are integrated into a mission-specific operating concept for the LiDARs. The results of the application described in this paper are intended to be integrated into the Operations Concept and flight software of the Dual-LiDAR system of the designated manufacturer Jena-Optronik GmbH for the ERO mission. Copyright © 2025 by the International Astronautical Federation (IAF). All rights reserved.
