TI  - Demonstrating Practical Attacks on Maritime Cyber-Physical Systems via Exposed NMEA Gateways
PY  - 2025
T2  - 2025 14th Mediterranean Conference on Embedded Computing, MECO 2025 - Proceedings
DO  - 10.1109/MECO66322.2025.11049124
UR  - https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105010461518?origin=resultslist
AB  - Maritime cyber-physical systems increasingly depend on networked components for navigation and coordination, exposing legacy protocols such as NMEA 0183 to remote exploitation. While previous research has analyzed vulnerabilities in onboard systems and maritime protocols, few studies have demonstrated practical attacks that exploit exposed NMEA gateways over the public internet.In this paper, we categorize and demonstrate four realistic attack vectors targeting NMEA-over-TCP interfaces, identified through testing on a certified gateway device. These include Global Positioning System (GPS) spoofing, Automatic Identification System (AIS) injection, autopilot manipulation, and resource exhaustion. We demonstrate the feasibility of these attacks using publicly available tools and emulated navigation software.Our work is the first to bridge real-world internet exposure with hands-on attack demonstrations against maritime NMEA systems, offering practical insights into the threat landscape. The findings reveal how unauthenticated access to these data streams can compromise critical vessel functions, underscoring the urgent need for improved protocol-level defenses.  © 2025 IEEE.
