TI  - A Machine Learning-based Intelligent Middleware Platform for a Private Edge Cloud
PY  - 2025
T2  - MIDDLEWARE Tutorials 2025 - Proceedings of the 2025 International Middleware Conference Tutorial Track, Part of Middleware 2025
SP  - 7
EP  - 8
DO  - 10.1145/3776592.3777489
UR  - https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105026183549?origin=resultslist
AB  - The deployment of fifth-generation (5G) and 802.11-based networks has enabled a new class of smart applications, such as extended reality and healthcare digital twins. These applications have diverse requirements, including low latency, high data rates, substantial computing and storage resources, and access to IoT devices. To meet these requirements, several edge computing systems, such as cloudlet computing, mobile edge computing, and fog computing, have been proposed. However, the deployment of edge computing systems often requires adding new infrastructure or extending existing systems. Moreover, current edge computing approaches do not fully utilize the capabilities of end devices, such as smartphones, mobile robots, and smart vehicles, which are equipped with multi-core CPUs and GPUs, numerous sensors, and multiple wireless communication interfaces.; AB@In contrast to publicly available edge computing solutions, private or local edge cloud systems have recently been proposed to further reduce latency, security risks, and privacy concerns, while improving bandwidth utilization and leveraging the capabilities of high-end devices. A private edge cloud system is a small-scale cloud data center deployed within a local physical environment, such as a house or an office. It consists of various stationary and mobile devices, including personal computers, mobile robots, smartphones, and sensors, interconnected through one or more local area networks.; AB@Nevertheless, to efficiently manage and utilize the private edge cloud infrastructure, intelligent middleware platforms are required-platforms that differ from those used in public edge cloud environments. In this tutorial, we will discuss the design of intelligent multinetwork protocols, resource management algorithms, and system platforms that leverage approaches such as machine learning, software-defined networking, and container technologies to (1) efficiently manage heterogeneous compute and network resources in a private edge environment, and (2) provide task processing, data collection, and data storage services to support emerging resource-intensive and non-resource-intensive smart applications.; AB@The tutorial will enable participants to:; ABbull; Understand major edge computing architectures and platforms.; ABbull; Gain knowledge of approaches and methods for building private edge cloud systems.; ABbull; Explore the use of machine learning, software-defined networking, and container technologies to enhance system performance and efficiency.; ABbull; Identify current research challenges and future opportunities in private edge computing for 5G and beyond. © 2025 Copyright held by the owner/author(s).
