AB  - Indoor drones have the potential to enhance material handling efficiency in intralogistics operations. Indoor drones offer rapid aerial mobility and have the potential to be used as a swarm or in collaboration with Automated Guided Vehicles (AGVs). However, implementing this system is challenging as it involves coordination between multiple components. Primarily, the communication protocols become complicated once the system scales. There will also be safety concerns. Implementing a digital twin (DT) methodology can help mitigate these risks and improve scalability. This study presents a preliminary digital shadow prototype that imitates the movement of an indoor drone using an interactive sensing system. While not a complete DT, this work serves as an early technical exploration focused on assessing suitable sensors for tracking and mirroring drone movement. The results provide foundational insights that can inform future development toward a fully functional DT system with bidirectional communication and predictive capabilities.  © 2025 The Author(s). 
