AB  - With the continual growth and increasing model complexities of smart-grid power systems, this work has attempted to design a fractional-order (FO), finite-time non-singular terminal sliding-mode controller (NS-TSMC) to achieve resilient frequency regulatory requirements against stealthy deception (FDI) cyber-attacks and unsteady load demand. The unknown stealthy FDI attacks are estimated employing a FO disturbance observer (FODO). The asymptotic convergence of the estimation error has been confirmed using the Mittag-Leffler stability method. Subsequently, NS-TSMC with estimated FDI attack/plant uncertainties is applied to retain the synchronism of power systems and increase grid resiliency. The exponential stability of the applied control system is studied and presented applying the Lyapunov method. Simulation results performed on Kuntur's two-area four-machine and IEEE 39-bus New-England testbeds have demonstrated proficiency and the disturbance suppression ability of the applied robust cyber-tolerant frequency control framework against stealthy FDI-attack.  © 2023 IEEE.
