AB  - The harsh and uncertain operational profile that characterizes the service life of a vessel amplifies the need for developing a method able to monitor the degradation of its structural integrity. Such a method will serve the transition to Condition monitoring of ship hull structures, a field that has gained the interest of researchers. In this work a structural health monitoring framework is proposed under the conceptual basis of digital twining. The present approach emphasizes the inverse identification of loads acting on the ship's hull via the readings of strain sensors in a output-only setting. The loading profile is then applied to the numerical model of the subject vessel for the estimation of the stress field at critical areas prone to fatigue damage. The proposed framework is evaluated by synthetic strain data derived from a finite element (FE) model of a Container Vessel. The results demonstrate the feasibility of the proposed approach for addressing the load identification problem and acts as a starting point for the development of a structural Digital Twin monitoring fatigue accumulation of hull structures. © 2024 11th European Workshop on Structural Health Monitoring, EWSHM 2024. All rights reserved.
