SP  - 467
EP  - 484
DO  - 10.51202/9783181024225-467
UR  - https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/85175165464?origin=resultslist
AB  - The quality and reliability is one of the most significant factor for every product in drive technology. Therefore, the simulative mapping of all characteristics and functions of a gear unit, its so-called digital twin, plays an increasingly important role. The actual focus is not only on mapping the mechanical properties, but also on analyzing the fluid flow to ensure the lubrication of all components and increase the energy efficiency of a gear unit. The field of CFD (“Computational Fluid Dynamics”) offers a particle-based simulation method called SPH (“Smoothed Particle Hydrodynamics”), which is used by SEW-EURODRIVE GmbH & Co KG (short: SEW) to analyze the fluid flow and evaluate the power losses for a wide range of gear unit variants in detail. In development and fundamental projects as well as in quality management the frontloading of simulations gives great opportunities to save resources like material, test capacities and workforce. In a first step, the quality of CFD simulations using the SPH method is analyzed by comparing the oil flow, especially local oil levels and splashing effects, of a planetary test gear unit with results of the simulation. This optical validation serves as a basis for all further simulations. Focus of this study is the evaluation of the fluid flow of 2- & 3-stage planetary gear units dependent on different gear unit sizes and rotation speed. Analyzing the wetting of every component of the gear unit and the volumetric flow rate in every gear contact of the sun wheel of the high-speed shaft shows the reliability of the lubrication concept. The last investigation is the analysis of the pumping effect of the gearing into an oil expansion tank at vertical mounting positions. Main aim is the definition of an ideal position of the piping to prevent the overflow of the tank and in general to show the potential of the SPH method to answer specific questions in drive technology. © 2023 the authors.
