AB  - This paper focuses on constructing a graph neural network deep learning model to analyse malicious Web requests and make timely warnings, in addition to generating adversarial samples for graph data structures through PGD topology attacks, conducting adversarial training, constructing robust deep learning detection models, monitoring Web application server ports, improving the security of Web applications, and reducing the risk of potential threats to the system. Graph neural networks are a class of machine learning models for processing graph data. The main goal of graph neural networks is to extend the idea of neural networks to graph data in order to better capture the relationships and features between nodes. PGD topology attack is an adversarial attack method against GNNs, where the attacker spoofs the model by modifying the representation of the graph data. Therefore in this project, strategies to defend against PGD attacks are considered while constructing the GNN model in order to improve the robustness of the model. To better clarify our research motivations and gaps, let us review related work. Researchers have proposed secure data transfer and trustworthy judgement methods for cyber-physical attacks in an integrated data-driven framework [12]. While this research looks at integrating data-driven frameworks, our research focuses on deeper web application security, especially on deep learning models and countering attacks when dealing with graph data. By introducing graph neural networks and adversarial training strategies, our work attempts to bridge the gap between existing approaches to improve the overall security of web applications. © 2023 ACM.
