AB  - Taking a typical high-vacuum-multilayer-insulation (HVMLI) liquid hydrogen horizontal storage tank as the object, a failure monitoring method of liquid hydrogen storage tank based on the temperature field of tank interlayer is discussed by combining real-time detection with numerical simulation. For the HVMLI structure, the outermost temperature of the insulation layer is calculated by the layer-by-layer heat transfer calculation method. Based on Fluent, the heat and mass transfer simulation of the tank model was carried out. Based on the MultiZone mesh division of the combination of tetrahedron and hexahedron, the energy equation, the standard K-epsilon turbulence model and the solar radiation model were selected to calculate the stable temperature field cloud map of the tank interlayer. Three common failure modes are simulated. The results show that compared with the normal working conditions, the outermost temperature field of the insulation layer will change significantly under the three failure modes. Combined with the conventional parameters such as the liquid level of the inner tank and the interlayer pressure, a multi-parameter fusion liquid hydrogen storage tank failure criterion is proposed, which can effectively judge the liquid phase leakage of the inner tank, the gas phase leakage of the inner tank, the leakage of the outer tank and the damage of the local insulation layer. Based on DTS technology, the safe and effective measurement of the temperature field on the outer surface of the insulation layer can be realized, and the twin model of liquid hydrogen storage tank driven by sensing data can be established to effectively judge the failure state. © 2024 by ASME.
