UR  - https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/85125735460?origin=resultslist
AB  - Ship emission monitoring is an interdisciplinary research problem involving the atmospheric environment, transportation, information communication, and computer technology. Maritime institutions and shipping companies are also important participants. However, to scientifically organize ship emission monitoring information to promote policy implementation for the introduction of more emission control areas (ECAs), data acquisition, transmission, and analysis, as well as information services, face great challenges. To address these issues, this study proposes a paradigm for constructing a ship emission monitoring sensor web (SEMSW) that includes the following key technologies: (1) multi-platform collaborative monitoring; (2) association processing of heterogeneous information; (3) real-time data transmission and online-processing; and (4) customized information services for different users. Since 2016, based on these technologies and the associated theories, a model SEMSW has been gradually established and operated in China's Waigaoqiao port area. This model SEMSW now plays an active role in scientific research and maritime law enforcement and has become an indispensable network of the physical infrastructure. Additionally, this model demonstrates the potential for a wider SEMSW to be introduced, which could serve as a powerful cyber-physical spatiotemporal information infrastructure for research on ship emissions and for ship emission monitoring. © 2022 The Authors
