AB  - As a typical cyber-physical system, Mobile Crowdsensing (MCS) systems utilize widely used mobile devices (such as smartphones) to sense the physical environment, supporting ubiquitous mobile sensing applications between humans and the physical world. The proliferation of smart terminal devices such as Unmanned Aerial Vehicles (UAVs) and Unmanned Surface Vehicles (USVs) has driven the development from human-centric MCS to Heterogeneous Crowdsensing (HCS). In a HCS system, sensed data storage is crucial. Traditional cloud storage and edge storage cannot provide data storage services in remote areas lacking communication infrastructure coverage. Therefore, this paper investigates the sensed data storage problem in a HCS system composed of UAVs and USVs in an edge-free scenario. To enhance the reliability of sensed data storage, we employ multiple replicas for backup storage and conduct a collaborative optimization of storage reliability and system energy consumption. The goal is to minimize the total system cost under constraints of storage capacity and battery power. Consequently, we formulate this problem as a mixed-integer programming problem. To solve this problem, we propose a Deep Deterministic Policy Gradient (DDPG)-based algorithm, named 'HCS-DDPG'. Finally, after extensive comparative evaluations, HCS-DDPG demonstrates the ability to reduce data loss rate by up to 30% and system energy consumption by up to 33% comnared to the ontimal baseline methods. © 2024 IEEE.
