EP  - 12
UR  - https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/85021757075?origin=resultslist
AB  - Increasing digitization offers the potential to further improve predictive maintenance through condition monitoring, ensuring maintenance is only undertaken when it  is genuinely needed. Offering a more intelligent approach to the maintenance regime, using prevention rather than cure, therefore, results in real time and cost benefits that are deliverable now. Increased automation at Festo's factory has enhanced the role of maintenance and led to a greater emphasis on sharing knowledge.  The Scharnhausen Technology Plant is Festo's main production facility for valves, valve terminals, and control electronics, covering 66,000m2 of space  arranged over four levelsand housing a workforce of around 1200 people. To create the Industry 4.0 environment, Festo has either piggy backed intelligence onto  existing machines or embedded it in new equipment. The plant uses Near Field Communications (NFC) for digital maintenance support. This means that equipment  components can exchange data directly with the maintenance team without passing through a central database. For the maintenance team, this presents new ways to  interact with the factory equipment and gather useful data. Their main tool is a tablet with a mobile depth sensor, enables the user to acess more information the  closer they are to the components requiring attention. At the high level the tablet may show an ovreview graphic of the entire plant layout and indicate that there is  an alert raised on a machine on a production line. For less serious events, information about the reasons for the alert can be interrogated remotely without any need  to interrupt production. Augmented reality is another exciting area under development. The concept of a Digital Twin - a CAD generated model that enables designers to  simulate how a machine will function, is already possible.
