AB  - Machine Learning (ML) has been implemented with great successes in recent decades, both in research and in practice. In the field of Cyber-Physical Systems (CPS), ML methods are already widely used, e.g. in anomaly detection, predictive maintenance or diagnosis use cases. However, Representation Learning (RepL), which learns general concepts from data and has been a major driver of improvements, is hardly utilized so far. To be useful for CPS, RepL methods would have to produce interpretable results, work without requiring much prior knowledge, and be applicable to typical CPS datasets, including e.g. noisy sensor signals and discrete system state changes. In this paper, we provide an overview of the current state of research regarding methods for learning physical concepts in time series data, which is the primary form of sensor data of CPS. We also analyze the most important methods from the current state of the art using the example of a three-tank system. Based on concrete implementations1, we discuss the advantages and disadvantages of the methods and show for which purpose and under which conditions they can be used for CPS. © 2022 Elsevier B.V.. All rights reserved.
